I"­	<p>Last month we introduced search functions.  We highlighted image search, which lets product developers use AI to explore their image database based on a text or image prompt.  But we also released text search, which as you may have guessed, allows developers to to search their text database with a text or image prompt.</p>

<h2 id="ways-to-use-text-search">Ways To Use Text Search</h2>

<p>The first and most obvious way to use text search is to semantically search your database.  Load the rows of a digital address book into Nyckel - now your users can perform searches that will find â€œlawyerâ€ when they search â€œattorneyâ€, or â€œprevious dentistâ€ when they type â€œmy old hygienistâ€.</p>

<p>But there are also a few ways to use text search that are less obvious:</p>

<p>Perhaps youâ€™re a toy store, building an app to suggest toys based on an image your customer is viewing.  Import the name of each toy into your search set, and query by the image.  Off-the-shelf APIs might return â€œBackhoeâ€ or â€œExcavatorâ€, but your toy is listed as â€œDiggerâ€.  Giving Nyckel a closed set of words to choose from gives you the best approximate match.</p>

